messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path for the endpoint
- /api/paste/public

Method acceptability based on the code (for this path)
- HEAD: true
  - Rationale: There is a GET mapping for this path. Spring MVC handles HEAD requests automatically for GET endpoints by returning the response headers without the body.
- GET: true
  - Rationale: The endpoint is explicitly annotated with @GetMapping(path = "/public").
- OPTIONS: true
  - Rationale: Spring MVC provides automatic handling of OPTIONS for endpoints with mappings, reflecting allowed methods.
- TRACE: false
  - Rationale: There is no TRACE mapping or explicit support in the code. Without explicit support, TRACE is not exposed by the endpoint.
- POST: false
  - Rationale: There is a @PostMapping defined, but at the class level it maps to /api/paste, not /api/paste/public. Therefore, POST to /api/paste/public is not defined in the code.
- PUT: false
  - Rationale: No PUT mapping for /api/paste/public exists.
- DELETE: false
  - Rationale: No DELETE mapping for /api/paste/public exists.
- PATCH: false
  - Rationale: No PATCH mapping for /api/paste/public exists.

Summary explanation
- The endpoint is defined only for GET at /api/paste/public, with no path variables.
- Spring will also support HEAD for GET mappings and OPTIONS for the endpoint by default.
- Other HTTP methods (POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH) are not mapped for this specific path, so they are not acceptable according to the code.
- TRACE is not supported by this endpoint as there is no TRACE mapping or framework-level exposure in the code.
